What are Arrays?
Arrays are collections of elements of the same data type.

Array Properties:
1. Stores data in contingency memory format.
2. Arrays are static; once the size of an array is declared, it can't be changed.
3. Arrays are indexed, starting from 0 to (size -1).
   eg. size of an array 6, then the elements can be stored from index 0 to 5.
4. The advantage of Arrays over Linked lists is that in arrays, there is no memory overhead (wastage of memory).

Arrays Types:
1. One-dimensional arrays (1D) eg. a[0]
2. Two-dimensional arrays (2D) - like a matrix eg. a[0][0], a[0][1], a[1][0], a[1][1]

Keywords in the code:-
1. stdio.h - It is a header file in C. It contains declarations for standard input and output functions like printf & scanf
2. int main() - This is the main function of a C program. Execution starts from here; int means this function returns an integer value to the operating system.
Usually, return 0 is written at the end to show the program ended successfully.
3. printf - the function is used to display output on the screen
4. scanf - the function is used to take input from the user. It only prints output
5. for loop - a loop is used to repeat a block of code until a condition becomes false.
   Syntax: for(initialization; condition; increment/decrement)
   eg. for(i = 0; i < n; i++)
      i = 0 → starting value of the loop variable
      i < n → loop runs while this condition is true
      i++ → after each iteration, i increases by 1
      \ n - print the output on a new line
      \t - an escape sequence in C used inside strings

# Creation of 1D array 
#include<stdio.h>
int main()
{
   int n, i, a[10];
   printf("Enter no of elements: ");
   scanf("%d", &n);
   for(i=0;i<n;i++)
   {
      printf("\n Enter value for %d index: ",i);
      scanf("%d", &a[i]);
   }
   printf("\n The array is: ");
   for(i=0;i<n;i++)
   {
      printf("%d\t",a[i]);
   }

return 0;
}

